I have this following structure in my collection

 

 
{code:java}
{
 "userID": "1234",
 "name": "Prakash",
 "email": "prakash@example.com",
 "street1": "some street 1",
 "street2" : "some street 2",
 "city" : "some city",
 "state": "some state",
 "country": "some country"          
}{code}
I am using the following struct (Address struct embedded)


{code:java}
type User struct {
   UserID string `bson:"userID"`
   Name string `bson:"name"`
   Email string `bson:email"`
   Address
}

type Address struct {
   Street1 string `bson:"street1"`
   Street2 string `bson:"street2"`
   City string `bson:"city"`
   State string `bson:"state"`
   Country string `bson:"country"`
}{code}
 

 

So, When I do

 
{code:java}
user := &User{}
collection.FindOne(ctx, bson.M{"userID": "1234"}).Decode(user)
{code}
I am getting the userID, Name and Email field *but the address fields are blank*.

 

 

And when I am using this user struct, *everything is working fine* and

I am getting all data from MongoDB as required.

 
{code:java}
type User struct {
    UserID string `bson:"userID"`
    Name string `bson:"name"`
    Email string `bson:email"`
    Street1 string `bson:"street1"`
    Street2 string `bson:"street2"`
    City string `bson:"city"`
    State string `bson:"state"`
    Country string `bson:"country"`
}{code}

This can be considered a follow-up of [GODRIVER-842|https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/GODRIVER-842], that the custom interfaces inside arrays or structs cannot be marshaled.

Example is shown as follows:

{code:example.go}
type I interface {}

type A struct {
	X string
}

type B struct {
	Y I
}

func (*A) Hello() {}

func main() {
	a := A{X: "meow"}
	b := B{Y: &a}
	_, err := bson.Marshal(b)
	fmt.Println(err)
}
{code}

It returns "{{no encoder found for main.I}}" in current state.  However, bson.Marshal can actaully work with interface{} inside struct, as well as custom interfaces if it is not inside a struct, so I would expect interface{} inside struct should work.

